<FIRST>r a AM-Hijacking-Passengers     12-17 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hijacking-Passengers,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air China Passengers Recall Hijack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passengers on an Air China jet hijacked en
route from Beijing to New York said Sunday the flight was
frightening even though they didn't know the plane had been
commandeered until it landed in Japan.
   ``The rumors were spreading around the plane; we didn't know
what was happening,'' said Ann Ofstedal, who said she had been
studying for the past three years at a Beijing university.
   ``Even from talking to the crew, we could get very little
information,'' she told reporters at San Francisco International
Airport. ``They said they were also very worried.''
   Flight 981 was flying from Beijing to New York via Shanghai and
San Francisco on Saturday when Zhang Zhenai ordered the plane to
fly to Seoul, South Korea. Korean authorities refused permission to
land, and the plane was diverted to Fukuoka Airport on Japan's
southern island of Kyushu.
   There, a purser reportedly pushed Zhang out the plane's rear
door, shattering his legs and pelvis. He was being treated at a
Japanese hospital.
   Authorities reported that Zhang, a 35-year-old cotton factory
foreman, threatened crew members with a knife. He reportedly told
Japanese police he participated in pro-democracy demonstrations in
China last June and decided to flee after the crackdown.
   Ofstedal said the crew at one point asked passengers for rope.
Although no one was told why it was needed, she said there was
speculation an overwrought passenger needed to be subdued. Later,
she said she heard Zhang had been tied up with the rope with the
help of passengers.
   The plane returned to Beijing with 185 of its 200 passengers,
including Zhang's wife and 10-year-old son. Police and airline
officials said they did not know what happened to them, but foreign
reporters saw the wife led from the plane in handcuffs.
   The flight to New York then resumed on a new aircraft. China's
Civil Aviation Administration said most of the passengers were
Chinese. Japanese police said there were 19 non-Chinese, including
12 Americans.
   Ofstedal said she became suspicious when the flight from Beijing
to Shanghai, which normally takes 1 hour and 45 minutes, lasted
more than two hours and the plane spent more than an hour circling
a small island.
   ``People were acting very calm,'' she said, ``but it was
obviously very tense.''
   Wang Yuan of Beijing said she didn't realize a hijacking was
taking place, although she and others were worried because the
flight to Shanghai was taking so long.
   When the plane flew to Fukuoka, she said through a translator,
passengers knew something was wrong when they looked out the
windows and saw tall buildings and roadways full of cars, an
unusual sight in China.
   Asked if she was sympathetic to Zhang's comments that he was
motivated by fear of reprisals for speaking out against his
government, Ofstedal replied, ``I think he could have chosen a
better way.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891217-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-17-89 1939EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     12-17 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rocket Attacks Kill 10 in Kabul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S.-backed insurgents rocketed
Afghanistan's capital Sunday, killing 10 people and wounding 27,
official Afghan radio said.
   Radio Kabul, monitored in Islamabad, said the rebels fired three
U.S.-made rockets from the Paghman heights about 15 miles west of
Kabul. It did not say what kind of rockets were used.
   The guerrillas claimed earlier in the day they had killed 50
troops of the Communist government who tried to dislodge them from
the strategic heights in fighting Dec. 11-13.
   MIDIA, a rebel news agency, also reported heavy losses on both
sides in northern clashes near the Soviet border.
   Radio Kabul blamed Sunday's rocketing of Kabul on the
fundamentalist Ittehad-i-Islami rebel party of Abdul Rasul Sayyaf.
It said children were among the casualties.
   Afghanistan's Soviet-backed government has reported hundreds of
civilians killed in guerrilla rocket attacks on the capital since
June.
   In its telex dispatch, the MIDIA agency said rebels killed 20
government officers and 30 soldiers when troops attacked guerrilla
positions in Paghman. It also said the guerrillas destroyed three
tanks and five other military vehicles while repelling the attack.
   It said two rebels and two civilians were also killed in the
fighting.
   Official Afghan media have not reported any such offensive, but
Radio Kabul claimed on Dec. 15 that government forces found and
destroyed 50 rebel rockets in the Paghman area.
   MIDIA also said Sunday that clashes occurred Dec. 6 and Dec. 8
in Daulatabad in northern Balkh province, about 27 miles south of
the Soviet border.
   It claimed that 22 government troops and militiamen were killed,
and 20 deserted to the rebel side.
   The agency said the government responded with heavy bombing and
shelling that killed 20 rebels and civilians, including two
guerrilla commanders it identified as Chari and Mohammad Nabi. It
said 40 other people were wounded.
   ``Fighting is still going on in full swing,'' MIDIA said.
   The ruling People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan seized power
in a 1978 military coup that set off the insurgency. Soviet forces
ended nine years of military intervention on Feb. 15, but Moscow
continues to back the ruling Marxists.
   Despite predictions of their early defeat after the Soviet
pullout, government forces continue to hold Afghanistan's major
cities. The guerrillas, who are based in Pakistan, reportedly
control most of the rugged countryside.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
