spokesman Michael Sheehan said.
   He told inspectors he had come to Miami to visit a heart doctor,
but was taken to Jackson Memorial Hospital for X-rays after he
displayed nervous and suspicious behavior, Sheehan said Saturday.
   At the hospital Thursday evening, Parra-Londono admitted
swallowing cocaine pellets, and as of Saturday had passed more than
100 weighing about two pounds, Sheehan said. No formal charges will
be filed until Parra-Londono had finished passing the pellets, he
added.
   In an unrelated case Friday, Peruvian Congressman Enrique Lujan
Pujada, 48, was arrested and charged with failing to declare more
than $25,000 in cash.
   He initially told inspectors when he arrived aboard an Aero Peru
flight that he had $5,000 in cash and another $5,000 in checks. But
when inspectors said they intended to pat him down, he admitted he
had more cash, and they found $30,280 in his pockets, Sheehan said.
</TEXT>
